    "summary": "The Satavahana Dynasty (c. 100 BC – 220 AD) was one of the most important early historical dynasties of the Deccan and central India, establishing the first major post-Mauryan state in peninsular India and serving as a crucial link in the trade networks connecting Rome, Arabia, and Southeast Asia.\n\nOriginating in the Deccan, the Satavahanas rose to prominence after the decline of Mauryan power and at their height controlled much of modern Maharashtra, Telangana, and Andhra Pradesh. They were patrons of both Brahmanical and Buddhist traditions, constructing numerous stupas and cave temples (notably at Amaravati and Karle). Their location made them key intermediaries in [[event:1110|Indian Ocean Trade Routes]], facilitating commerce between Rome and the east. Their coins — bilingual in Prakrit and Tamil in some cases — reflect engagement with both northern and southern India. The dynasty's Prakrit inscriptions are among the earliest literary records of the Deccan.",
